### Group B — Backend TypeScript / Express Handler Fixes (Requirements 4, 5, 6)

#### Fix B1 — Coupon Routes: ObjectId Guards and Missing Returns (Requirement 4)

**File:** `matasree-backend/src/routes/couponRoutes.ts`

Two issues:

1. The `POST /apply` handler assigns `coupon.usedOrderId` and `coupon.userId` without `return` guards after earlier `res` calls, risking double-response crashes.
2. The ObjectId constructor is called unconditionally, which can throw if `orderId` or `userId` is undefined.

**Changes to `POST /apply` handler:**

All `res.status(...).json(...)` calls in conditional branches must be prefixed with `return`. The ObjectId assignments must be guarded:

```typescript
// BEFORE (excerpt)
if (coupon.isUsed) {
  return res.status(400).json(new ApiResponse(false, 'Coupon already used', null, 400));
}
// ... other checks without return ...
coupon.isUsed = true;
coupon.usedAt = new Date();
if (orderId) coupon.usedOrderId = new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(orderId);
if (authReq.user?.userId) coupon.userId = new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(authReq.user.userId);

// AFTER — every branch has return; ObjectId assignments are guarded
if (coupon.isUsed) {
  return res.status(400).json(new ApiResponse(false, 'Coupon already used', null, 400));
}
if (coupon.source === 'newsletter') {
  if (authReq.user && coupon.email.toLowerCase() !== authReq.user.email.toLowerCase()) {
    return res.status(400).json(new ApiResponse(false, 'This 10% off code belongs to another account', null, 400));
  }
  if (authReq.user) {
    const usedNewsletterCoupon = await Coupon.findOne({
      userId: authReq.user.userId, source: 'newsletter', isUsed: true
    });
    if (usedNewsletterCoupon) {
      return res.status(400).json(new ApiResponse(false, 'You have already used a 10% off welcome code', null, 400));
    }
  }
}
if (new Date() > coupon.expiresAt) {
  return res.status(400).json(new ApiResponse(false, 'Coupon expired', null, 400));
}
coupon.isUsed = true;
coupon.usedAt = new Date();
if (orderId && typeof orderId === 'string' && orderId.trim().length > 0) {
  coupon.usedOrderId = new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(orderId);
}
if (authReq.user?.userId && typeof authReq.user.userId === 'string') {
  coupon.userId = new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(authReq.user.userId);
}
await coupon.save();
return res.status(200).json(new ApiResponse(true, 'Coupon applied successfully', coupon));
```

**Changes to `POST /validate` handler:**

All branches that call `res.status(...).json(...)` must be prefixed with `return`. The final success response must also use `return`.

